bet use to illustrate that law is a vague and boggy realm where truth, and falsehood, is seldom absolute. With his lively, insightful, and sometimes hilarious prose, Lubet takes readers on a tour of the law in our everyday lives, and forces us to rethink how we really feel about honesty and truth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aJustice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aLegal ethicszUnited States. 0aPractice of lawxCorrupt practiceszUnited States. 0aTruthfulness and falsehood. 7aLAW / Ethics & Professional Responsibility.2bisacsh  aexploration.  anothing.  atruth.  awhole.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475221040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814753422.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814753422423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814753422/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK